<subSubSection box="[776,1138,597,630]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[776,1369,446,866]" box="[776,1138,597,630]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">This species is monotypic.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6657445" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6657445" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6657445/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" targetBox="[161,752,452,865]" targetPageId="9">
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[776,1369,446,866]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[776,952,632,670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Distribution.</emphasis>
Obi, Bisa, and Obilatu (= Obi-Latoe) Is in the NC Moluccas, Indonesia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[776,1369,446,866]" lastBlockId="9.[162,1370,876,1694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
Descriptive or notes. Head-body 36-39 cm, tail 30-33.5 cm; weight 1.1-1.4 kg. The Obi Cuscus is a relatively small cuscus (condylobasal length 65-69 mm). Skull of the Obi Cuscus is similar to that of the Moluccan Cuscus (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1860" box="[428,558,916,945]" class="Mammalia" family="Phalangeridae" genus="Phalanger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diprotodontia" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ornatus">P. ornatus</taxonomicName>
) and the Gebe Cuscus (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flannery &amp; Boeadi" authorityYear="1995" box="[892,1070,916,945]" class="Mammalia" family="Phalangeridae" genus="Phalanger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diprotodontia" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alexandrae">P. alexandrae</taxonomicName>
), and it bears a prominent diastema between incisor and canine but is smaller than those species and has smaller teeth. The Obi Cuscus has two color morphs: orange-brown or gray dorsal fur with dark underfur. Ventral fur is white to yellow. Dark dorsal stripe extends from head to mid-back or rump.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</caption>
<subSubSection box="[164,808,1109,1142]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[162,1370,876,1694]" box="[164,808,1109,1142]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[164,274,1109,1142]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Habitat.</emphasis>
Primary forest and regrowth habitats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="9.[162,1370,876,1694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[163,434,1148,1181]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Similar to other cuscuses, the Obi Cuscus is likely to be folivorous—frugivorous. Chewed acorns have been found under a large fruiting 
<taxonomicName box="[1219,1370,1188,1221]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Lithocarpus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Lithocarpus</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dumortier" authorityYear="1829" box="[176,306,1231,1260]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="9" pageNumber="490" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fagaceae</taxonomicName>
) used by Obi Cuscuses.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="9.[162,1370,876,1694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[163,297,1267,1300]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Breeding.</emphasis>
Female Obi Cuscuses collected in January had one young each, with sizes ranging from only 2 cm in length up to 99 g in body mass.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="9.[162,1370,876,1694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[162,395,1350,1379]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
There is no specific information available for this species, but the Obi Cuscus is no doubt nocturnal and spends its day resting in the canopy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[162,1370,876,1694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[163,875,1424,1457]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
There is no information available for this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="490" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="9.[162,1370,876,1694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[164,514,1503,1536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="490">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. Although the Obi Cuscus has a small extent of occurrence (less than 3000 km?) and is known only from three islands, it is thought to be relatively tolerant of habitat degradation, and the population is thought to be stable.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
